Date: 27 Mar 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Hong Kong - Department of Health [edited]
<http://www.info.gov.hk/dh/new/index.htm>

[A] Figures on atypical pneumonia 27 Mar 2003
The following is jointly issued by the Department of Health and the
Hospital Authority:
As at 1 PM 27 Mar 2003, a total of 367 people with pneumonia symptoms have
been admitted to public hospitals. The 51 additional patients reported
today include 6 healthcare workers and 22 patients from Amoy Garden. The
remaining 23 were new patients and contacts of patients with atypical
pneumonia.
As of 27 Mar 2003, 19 patients have been discharged from hospitals. A total
of 45 patients are receiving treatment in the intensive care unit. An
additional patient, a Filipino female with atypical pneumonia, died in
Queen Elizabeth Hospital on 24 Mar 2003.
DH confirmed 4 new cases of atypical pneumonia involving school children
comprising 3 boys and a girl aged from 5 to 13. These cases are among the
367 cases reported today.
Meanwhile, the Department of Health (DH) appealed to patients who had
consulted a private doctor, Dr Lau Tai Kwan, between 20-22 Mar 2003 to
contact the Department at 2760 7721 during office hours. Dr Lau suffered
from atypical pneumonia and has been included in the reported cases.
Dr Lau's clinic address is Room 130, Tung Ying Building, 100 Nathan Road,
Tsim Sha Tsui. He developed symptoms on 20 Mar 2003 and was admitted to
Princess Margaret Hospital on 22 Mar 2003.
DH and HA are pleased to see the development of rapid diagnostic test,
which facilitates prompt confirmation of severe respiratory syndrome cases
and evaluation of effectiveness of treatment.
"We have great appreciation for the efforts of the health professionals in
the management of atypical pneumonia, and the important research progress
of the University of Hong Kong and the Chinese University of Hong Kong
towards identification of the cause of the disease," a DH spokesman added.
The breakdown of figures is as follows:
Total Admissions (The numbers in bracket are those with pneumonia symptoms)
Health care workers of Hospitals/Clinics and medical students 149 (148)
10 of the patients were discharged
Patients, family members & visitors 221 (219)
9 of the patients were discharged
Total admissions 370 (367)
19 were discharged

[B] Ordinance amended to control infectious disease 27 Mar 2003
In order to enhance control over the spread of Severe Acute Respiratory
Syndrome (commonly known as atypical pneumonia) in the community, the
Director of Health, Dr Margaret Chan, on 27 Mar 2003 added Severe Acute
Respiratory Syndrome to the list of infectious diseases specified in the
First Schedule to the Quarantine and Prevention of Disease Ordinance (Hong
Kong Laws Chapter 141).
"This enables the application of the provisions of the Ordinance and its
subsidiary legislation as and when appropriate. This would enhance the
coverage of our infectious diseases surveillance system so that Department
of Health can better monitor the occurrence of Severe Acute Respiratory
Syndrome." Dr Chan said.
Regulation 4 of the Prevention of the Spread of Infectious Diseases
Regulations requires medical practitioners to notify the Director of Health
if they have reason to suspect the existence of any of the infectious
diseases specified in the First Schedule to the Ordinance.
"The reporting of infectious diseases is an important element of the
surveillance, control and prevention of outbreak of infectious diseases."
said Dr Chan.
Dr Chan reminded medical practitioners of the requirement to notify
Department of Health any suspected cases of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome.
Dr Chan exercised her power in accordance with sections 72 and 8(4) of the
Ordinance and amended the First Schedule to the Ordinance and Form 2 in the
Schedule to the Prevention of the Spread of Infectious Diseases Regulations
respectively by making the Quarantine and Prevention of Disease Ordinance
(Amendment of First Schedule) Order 2003 and the Prevention of the Spread
of Infectious Diseases Regulations (Amendment of Form) Order 2003.
With the addition of Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome, a total of 28
infectious diseases are included in the First Schedule to the Ordinance.
