[ProMED-mail would like to thank Marianne Hopp <mjhopp12@yahoo.com>, Dr
Rana Jawad Asghar <jawad@alumni.washington.edu>, John Herbert
<j_a_herbert@yahoo.com>, Cherie McCown <cmccown@md.okayama-u.ac.jp>, T.
Haydon <Teal414@aol.com> and Pamela Johnson <pamela@voxiva.net> for their
submissions.
The data reported by WHO above represent an increase of 85 cases in the
past 24 hours, of which 14 were in China, 51 were in Hong Kong SAR, China,
4 were in Singapore, and 9 were in Canada, all areas with local
transmission. There were an additional 5 suspected (not using the WHO
probable case definition) reported from the USA, where local transmission
has not yet been confirmed. There were an additional 4 deaths reported due
to SARS, with the case fatality rate based on today's numbers 3.7 percent.
The travel advisory recommendation by WHO contained in the Update 11 above
([1] [C]) is new, recommending that airlines begin screening passengers for
possible symptoms compatible with SARS for exclusion from travel. This
represents a real concern that there has now been documentation of
transmission of SARS on airplanes, as reflected in several countries'
recommendations that travel to the affected areas be postponed. - Mod.MPP]
